**Overall Meaning:**

"From holding the breath at the tip of the nose, long life and lightness of the body would be [achieved].  At the arrival of Brahma time [dawn], one should draw the breath in with the tongue."

**Explanation:**

This verse from the Upanishads continues to highlight the specific benefits of focusing pranayama on different energy centers. It suggests that focusing on the nose can promote longevity and physical lightness. It also recommends a specific practice of drawing the breath in at dawn, which is considered a spiritually auspicious time.

**Breakdown:**

* **"नासाग्रे धारणाद्दीर्घमायुः स्यात्":**  This indicates that holding the breath at the tip of the nose can lead to a long lifespan.
* **"देहलाघवम्":** This further emphasizes that this practice can also contribute to a lighter and more energized body.
* **"ब्राह्मे मुहूर्ते सम्प्राप्ते":** This describes the time of dawn, known as "Brahma muhurta," which is considered a spiritually potent time for meditation and practice.
* **"वायुमाकृष्य जिह्वया":** This instructs the practitioner to draw the breath in using the tongue, implying a specific technique for deep inhalation.

This verse emphasizes the connection between pranayama, specific energy centers, and time-sensitive practice. By aligning breathing techniques with the rhythm of the day and focusing on specific areas of the body, one can potentially achieve various benefits, including longevity and spiritual growth. 
